title: my report
text:
1 Quotations
There are several ways to include quotations in your document.

title: my report
text:
1.1 callout blocks

1.1.1 default






Note



Note that there are five types of callouts, including: note, warning, important, tip, and caution.




1.1.2 custom
By using the fenced-div syntax, quotes can be easily embedded in the text. This allows rendering to HTML and PDF with the same syntax. The following examples show the various possibilities.

1.1.2.1 without title
::: {.my-callout}

1.1.2.2 with title

title: my report
text:
1.2 colorbox
Using the latex package tcolorbox, you can include quotations in a colored box. This only works in PDF renders so far and isnt included in the HTML.

text:
2.1 Subheading Example
Here’s a look at simple text formatting in a Quarto document. This includes:

title: 2  Introduction
text:
Bold text for emphasis
Italicized text for titles or key terms
Inline code for highlighting code snippets within text

title: 3  Mathematical Content and Formulas

title: 4  Scientific Units and Special Characters
text:
This chapter demonstrates the use of scientific units and special characters:

Water boils at 100 °C.
The symbol for micro is µ.
The German letter ß is used in “straße,” meaning street.

title: 5  Interactive Content with Widgets
text:
5.1 Plotly Graph
library(plotly)

Loading required package: ggplot2



Attaching package: 'plotly'


The following object is masked from 'package:ggplot2':

    last_plot


The following object is masked from 'package:stats':

    filter


The following object is masked from 'package:graphics':

    layout

library(palmerpenguins)
data(penguins, package = "palmerpenguins")

plot_ly(data = penguins, x = ~bill_length_mm, y = ~bill_depth_mm, type = 'scatter', mode = 'markers')

Warning: Ignoring 2 observations








Figure 5.1: Scatter plot of bill length vs. bill depth in penguins.
Figure 5.1 shows a scatter plot of bill length vs. bill depth in penguins. You can hover over the points to see the data values. It is created using the plotly package.

title: 5  Interactive Content with Widgets
text:
5.2 Leaflet Map

library(leaflet)

# Placeholder data; replace with actual geographic data if available
leaflet() %>% 
  addTiles() %>% 
  addMarkers(lng = 174.768, lat = -36.852, popup = "Auckland")







Figure 5.2: Map showing a sample location. Note: Interactive features do not display in PDF.




Figure 5.2 shows a sample map with a marker at Auckland, New Zealand. It is created using the leaflet package. Note that interactive features do not display in PDF.

title: 6  Tables in Various Formats
text:
6.3 GT Tables (interactive)

library(gt)
library(palmerpenguins)

# interactive gt table

penguins %>% 
  select(species, island, bill_length_mm, bill_depth_mm) %>%
  head() %>%
  gt() %>%
  opt_interactive()



Table 6.3: A selection of measurements from the Palmer Penguins dataset.

title: 6  Tables in Various Formats
text:
6.4 really long tables

# interactive gt table

penguins %>% 
  select(species, island, bill_length_mm, bill_depth_mm, flipper_length_mm, body_mass_g) %>%
  gt() %>%
  tab_spanner(label = "Penguin Measurements", columns = c(species, island)) %>%
  tab_spanner(label = "Bill Measurements", columns = c(bill_length_mm, bill_depth_mm)) %>%
  tab_spanner(label = "Body Measurements", columns = c(flipper_length_mm, body_mass_g))
